{
  "slug": "the-electric-state-is-a-netflix-nightmare-plus-10-better-mov",
  "title": "‘The Electric State’ Is a Netflix Nightmare. Plus, 10 (Better) Movies We Missed.",
  "show": "The Big Picture",
  "network": "The Ringer",
  "hosts": [
    "Sean Fennessey",
    "Amanda Dobbins",
    "Chris Ryan"
  ],
  "published": "2025-03-17",
  "runtimeMin": 137,
  "format": "The Russos' $320M Netflix tentpole gets taken apart, then the crew catches up on ten films they skipped over a dire box-office weekend, before Sean sits down with his old friend Mark Anthony Green on his debut, 'Opus.'",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The box office and the shrinking theatrical window",
      "note": "Odyssey updates, VOD, and a $52M weekend",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "The Odyssey",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "Chris keeps dive-bombing the show with unverified Nolan casting rumors: Holland as Telemachus, Zendaya as Athena, Hathaway as Penelope. Sean wants a real plan, not X.com screenshots."
        },
        {
          "title": "Mickey 17",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Warner is putting it on VOD March 25, 17 days after release, the example everyone reaches for on the collapsing window."
        },
        {
          "title": "Black Bag",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Soderbergh's $50M adult drama that most of its target audience won't hear about until it streams."
        },
        {
          "title": "Anora",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Tom Quinn said it made eight figures in VOD profits, cited as the transparency the studios will never give."
        },
        {
          "title": "Captain America: Brave New World",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Clawing to barely $400M; not the Marvels-level disaster, but bad."
        },
        {
          "title": "Moana 2",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "A November release that only just hit Disney+, the last domino if Disney adopts the two-week window."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "‘The Electric State’ Is a Netflix Nightmare",
      "note": "the Russos' $320M streaming-only tentpole",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "The Electric State",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Adapted from Simon Stålenhag's crowdfunded illustrated novel. Millie Bobby Brown hunts for her brother across a post-robot-war 1994 with Chris Pratt and a Woody Harrelson-voiced Mr. Peanut; Stanley Tucci is evil Steve Jobs. Sean calls it one of the worst movies of the decade: the 'Chewbacca cheat' gone wide, where nothing is ever really at stake, and a distillation of everything wrong with big-budget studio filmmaking."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "10 (Better) Movies We Missed",
      "note": "the catch-up round",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Novocaine",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "The weekend's No. 1 at $8.7M. Jack Quaid as an assistant bank manager who can't feel pain; a winning first 45 minutes, then iterative violence. A fine mid-budget movie that would play great at home."
        },
        {
          "title": "Borderline",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Small 90s-set indie with Samara Weaving as a pop star and a very good Ray Nicholson as her unwell stalker, king-of-comedy energy."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Gorge",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Scott Derrickson's Apple movie: two hot snipers (Teller, Taylor-Joy) fall in love across a pit full of bioweapon demons. A great setup and first act, then it becomes Resident Evil. 'The purest distillation of COVID-era filmmaking.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "Last Breath",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Apollo 13 underwater, based on Alex Parkinson's own 2019 documentary. Gripping and genuinely suspenseful, if top-to-bottom miscast save Cliff Curtis. Soft recommend."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Monkey",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Oz Perkins' Stephen King horror-comedy, big on extravagant gory kills. Both hosts mixed on it, gore for gore's sake, but it makes more sense as a movie about processing a parent's death."
        },
        {
          "title": "Eephus",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Carson Lund's one-last-amateur-baseball-game movie, tactile and dreamlike. Bob loved it; a favorite of the year so far. Go support it."
        },
        {
          "title": "Becoming Led Zeppelin",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Bernard McMahon's IMAX doc, seen big. Pro-forma as documentary, overwhelming as a performance movie, and it only covers the first two records. Sean would rather this replace the Bohemian Rhapsodys of the world."
        },
        {
          "title": "Chaos: The Manson Murders",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "The new Errol Morris doc, based on Tom O'Neill's book. Flat: over-reliant on archival zoom-ins, not enough O'Neill. It breaks Sean's heart to say it's not good."
        },
        {
          "title": "Love Hurts",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "The Ke Huy Quan movie. Terrible: 83 minutes, looks shot on the Good Place set. Made Novocaine feel a lot better."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Actor",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Andre Holland as an actor who wakes up amnesiac in small-town Ohio, from a 1960 Donald Westlake story. Great premise, but a dreamlike style Sean found distancing; it came and went."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "interview",
      "heading": "Mark Anthony Green on ‘Opus’",
      "note": "the writer-director, and one of Sean's oldest friends",
      "guest": "Mark Anthony Green on",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Opus",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "His 19-day debut: Ayo Edebiri as a young magazine writer, John Malkovich as a reclusive pop star at his A-plus. Green flew to Riga to convince a one-eyed Malkovich not to wreck the schedule; Nile Rodgers and The-Dream wrote the original songs nearly for free. On tribalism, being challenged, and the 13 years he spent at GQ."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
